@endnode
@node "5" "File Lister Express (FLE) by Peter Zelezny & Glen Martin"

 .----------------.     _   /|
 |                |     \'o.O'
 |  Installation  |     =(_._)=
 |                |        U    FLE (c) Glen Martin of GREMLiNS BBS
 `----------------'

 Follow each of the steps below, and you can't go run in installing
 the great File Lister Express. If you have probs, see the Help/Support
 section for guidence.

 Firstly, unpack the archive to RAM: and click on the FLE_install icon.
 Once the installation process has finished, read below:

 Also, refer to the Changes/Info section of the guide!

 .----------.
 | Step One |
 `----------'

 o Lines you must add to the "text cfg" in MAXs BBS:

 349  Rest of marked files won't be sent due to lack of credits^M%Z
 348  [H]elp [M]ark [V]iewArc [i]nfo [S]top [CR]Continue
 347  ^[[20;3HUse this description (Yes/n)?^[[K
 346  ^M^MLog off after downloading (y/No)?
 345  ^[[20;3HEnter file description (?? Lines Max)^[[K
 344  ^L^M^Mincomplete Transfer(s):
 343  ^[[0;1;44m 
 342  ^[[20;3HUse your upload signature (Yes/n)?
 341  ^[[0;1;31m Not enough credits!^[[0m
 339  ^[[20;3HSaving to list...^[[K
 338  ^M^MSaving to list...^[[K
 182  ^M
 153  ^[[34m

 Line 153 is the color of the "no. of downloads" in the file list.
 Line 343 is the color of the numbers in the file list.
 Line 182 must be made blank!!

 (?? = No. of lines you set in your config for description)

 .----------.
 | Step Two |
 `----------'

 Now you'll have to configure the "Menus cfg" part of MAXs BBS.
 Menu functions you'll have to change with a door:

 ListFiles <areanumber> [<layoutnumber>]
 Dnload 
 Upload <areanumber>
 EditMarkList
 UnMarkAll
 Newfiles [<layoutnumber>]
 FileGraph
 FLETextList <filepath/ansi_filename>

 If you specify an area number of "0" when using the ListFiles door
 It'll list ALL files that the user has access to.

 eXAMPLE: You have an option like "(L)ist Files in area 21" then you'd
          configure MAXs BBS like this:

 KEY    FUNC   EXTRA   LOWAXS  HiGHAXS  FiLE/PATH/DOOR
  L      34      0        0     10000    FLE:ListFiles 21

 Now all you have to do is go through all your menus and change any
 functions that have something to do with MAXs old filebase.

 Also you have to run the "NewFiles" door somewhere in the login
 sequence, this could be in maindoor.text or simular.

 .------------.
 | Step Three |
 `------------'

 Now its time to edit all the files found in the "Doors:Filebase/Config/"
 directory. Just load them into your favourite text editor, they are all
 self explanatory and most have little comments in them to assist you.

 Also, you can edit/change some of the ansi screens.

 .-----------.
 | Step Four |
 `-----------'

 You must now assign FLE. Edit your user-startup and add the line
 "Assign FLE: BBS:Doors/FileBase/"

 Always use the path FLE: when executing a program, eg: FLE:dnload.

 .-----------.
 | Step Five |
 `-----------'

 Run FLE_config (via shell) and edit the configuration details.

 .----------.
 | Step Six |
 `----------'

 You must, if need be, edit your "Sections.txt" located in your
 FLE config directory. 

 After you have done this, run the FLE_Optimiser. This will create the
 needed files in "Files/DataFiles/" directory to use FLE.

 .------------.
 | Step Seven |
 `------------'

 Change everyone's ratio in MAXs UserEditor to "0". This can be done
 but changing one user's ratio to "0" and press the tick next to it and
 then clicking the Global button, then save. MAXs BBS file ratio is
 not used as FLE's uses it's own ratio system.

 .------------.
 | Step Eight |
 `------------'

 Reboot system, and if all is done correctly (and goes well), then FLE
 should work just fine. Log onto your BBS and start testing. See the
 Debugging section for any probs or Help/Support section for guidance.

@endnode
@node "6" "File Lister Express (FLE) by Peter Zelezny & Glen Martin"

 .------------.     _   /|
 |            |     \'o.O'
 |  Sections  |     =(_._)=
 |            |        U    FLE (c) Glen Martin of GREMLiNS BBS
 `------------'

 The installation program will create this file for you but future editing
 of the file and changing the "Flags" is up to you. Initially, there would
 be changes to suit your filebase settings, paths, etc.

 .-------------------.
 | Sections.txt File |
 `-------------------'

 The structure of the "Sections.txt" file is as follows:

   Section number
   Access, 0, 0
   Max userdiz lines, Max filediz lines, Max filelength name
  Name of section
  File path
  Flags
  User Flags (not used)

 eXAMPLE:

   18
   10, 0, 0
   6, 12, 16
  Amiga games
  Files:Games/    (must have "/" or ":" on the end)
  ---Y----Y---
  --------        (must be eight chars)


 nOTE: If you add/delete sections, you must run the FLE_Optimiser
       straight after, to update the changes to the filebase settings.

 aTTENTiON: Problems may occur if section number exceeds 99. Keep section
            numbers between 1 and 99 in "Section.txt", if possible!

            Previous docs may have mentioned the settings of MaxMegs and
            MaxFiles (set after the Access), which is shown above as
            "Access, 0, 0". MaxMegs and MaxFiles has been removed from
            FLE as it was buggy (and useless), so ensure these are set
            too "0" in the "Sections.txt" (as above example shows).

 .-------.
 | Flags |
 `-------'

 They are different options you can enable in each file area. There
 are 12 settings that can be set (it must be only 12 characters long).

 These flags are as follows:

    ------------
    ||||||||||||
    |||||||||||`----------------------+ Force to newfiles check?
    ||||||||||`-----------------------+ Must be set as "-"
    |||||||||`------------------------+ Must be set as "-"
    ||||||||`-------------------------------------------------.
    |||||||`-----------------------------------------------.  |    
    ||||||`------------------------------------------.     |  +
    |||||`-----------------------------------.       +     | Allow U/L
    ||||`-----------------------.            | Exec Upload | Signatures?
    |||`----------------.       |            | Master File +
    ||`----------.      |       |            |            Exec
    +`-----.     |      |       |            |            Upload File
 Must be   |     |      +       +            +
 set as "-"|     |    Unpack  Description  Creditless
           +     +   File_id? to Filenote?   Area?
      New Files Are Files  
       Public?   Free?


 If you want the option on, just put in a "Y" and if you don't then just
 put in a "-". An example setting showing "---Y-------" would enable only
 unpacking of file_id.diz and nothing else.

 .-------------------------.
 | Description to Filenote |
 `-------------------------'

 This adds the first 70 letters of the description to the uploaded file's
 "Filenote". This is the dos comment field.

 .-----------------.
 | Creditless Area |
 `-----------------'

 The creditless area is an area where users do not get any credits for
 uploading files. You may want this for a text files area or some other
 area which you don't want users uploading to to just get some cheap
 credits.

 .----------------------------.
 | Execute Upload Master File |
 `----------------------------'

 This is for the more experienced FLE user.

 You can get FLE to execute a command line after a user has uploaded
 a file, this could be to remove banners from a DMS, add an advertisment
 for your BBS and even check CRC.

 The Master file is "Doors:Filebase/Config/MastUploadExec.txt" which
 has the following format (an example is included):

  Extension
  Flags
  Bad file text message
  Bad file keyword
  Text message
  Command line
  Command line
  ....
  -

 eXAMPLE:

  .DMS
  NN
  n/a
  n/a
  Removing banners from DMS file, please wait...
  sys:c/RemoveFront %F
  sys:c/RemoveAdverts %F
  -
  .LHA
  NY
  File has found to have a bad CRC and will be deleted!
  BAD CRC FOUND
  CRC in progress...
  Lha t %F
  -

 You can have as many command lines as you like but make sure you put
 the "-" to seperate it from the next extension. Also, you have one
 auto insert, which is %F and works exactly like in the Diz unpacking
 commands, where the program finds %F it will replace it with the
 filename just uploaded. You can also put escape codes in the Text
 Message as long as you don't exceed one line. If one line is not enough
 for you then you can specify an ansi filename and put a "<" in front
 of it, eg: <bbs:text/rembbsadverts.ans.

 What is the NN part you ask? Well they are the answers to 2 questions.
 The first one being, "Show output?" and second, "Check for bad string?".
 If you turn the 2nd flag on, FLE will check for the occurence of the
 Bad File Keyword, eg: When running a LHA CRC test and it finds a bad
 file it may say something like, "Bad lha archive file!", so you can
 put this string in the Bad File Keyword slot and FLE will delete that
 upload if the file is bad.

 .---------------------.
 | Execute Upload File |
 `---------------------'

 This is almost the same as the above, except that you can have a
 seperate file to execute for another area, which is called:

 "Doors:Filebase/Config/UploadExec.txt"

 .--------------------------.
 | Force to New Files Check |
 `--------------------------'

 This will do just that. Force all files in this area to the new files
 check, regardless of the files dates. This could be usefull for
 always displaying registration forms, etc, when NewFiles door is run
 upon login.

@endnode
@node "7" "File Lister Express (FLE) by Peter Zelezny & Glen Martin"

 .----------.     _   /|
 |          |     \'o.O'
 |  Ratios  |     =(_._)=
 |          |        U    FLE (c) Glen Martin of GREMLiNS BBS
 `----------'

 Before starting to use FLE properley you'll have to set your ratios
 up. When a new user logs on (could be just new to FLE), they are auto-
 matically given a KB and File ratio according to their access level. This
 is configured in the "Doors:Filebase/Config/UserDefaults.txt" file (an
 example config is included).

 nOTE: Change everyone's ratio in MAXs UserEditor to "0". This can be
       done but changing one user's ratio to "0" and press the tick next
       to it and then clicking the Global button, then save. MAXs BBS
       file ratio is not used as FLE's uses it's own ratio system.

 eXAMPLE: You want new users with access level 5 to get a 10:1 file
          ratio and a 6:1 KB ratio (the 6:1 KB ratio means that if they
          upload 100k, they can download 600k). Also, you want to grant
          these new users 1 Meg of free downloads to get them going on
          their first call, and also 10 file credits. This is how your
          userdefaults entry would look:

 ---------------------------------- NEW MEMBER ------------------
 ----- File Ratio, Kilobyte Ratio, ACCESS LEVEL and DN Limit:----
 10
 6
 5
 5000
 ----- Startup Kilobyte Credits and Startup File Credits: -------
 1000
 10

        Also note that with the above config, these users would get a
        5000k per day download limit. A setting of "0" is unlimited.


 nOTE:  o Do not remove the comments/guides from any data files.

        o A ratio of "0" means unlimited.

        o Both KB and File ratios can be from 0 to 255.

        o A ratio of 256 means No Credits, ie: if they upload a file
          they won't get any credits for it.

        o If you just want to use one type of ratio just set the other
          to 0 (unlimited).

        o A maximum of 12 axs levels only in UserDefaults.txt config.

@endnode
@node "8" "File Lister Express (FLE) by Peter Zelezny & Glen Martin"

 .-----------.     _   /|
 |           |     \'o.O'
 |  Layouts  |     =(_._)=
 |           |        U    FLE (c) Glen Martin of GREMLiNS BBS
 `-----------'

      tYPE: MAXs door
 aRGUMENTS: Listfiles <areanumber> [<layoutnumber>]
            NewFiles [<layoutnumber>]

 This layout argument is optional. If you leave it out completely it'll
 use the default. The layout is basically how the filelist will look when
 a user lists files. There are 3 options, here's an example of each below:

 LayOut 0 (default)

 01 gremlins.lha      274k 08-04-98 +------------------------------------+
                                    |   file_id.diz here                 |

 LayOut 1

 01 gremlins.lha     274k 02 080498 +------------------------------------+
                                    |   file_id.diz here                 |

 LayOut 2

 01 gremlins.lha    +------------------------------------+   274k 08-04-98
                    | file_id.diz here                   | 


 Layout 1 has a more compressed date format and also shows the number of
 times the file has been downloaded (02 times in the above example).

@endnode
@node "9" "File Lister Express (FLE) by Peter Zelezny & Glen Martin"

 .-----------.     _   /|
 |           |     \'o.O'
 |  Headers  |     =(_._)=
 |           |        U    FLE (c) Glen Martin of GREMLiNS BBS
 `-----------'

 These are ansi screens you can show above file lists. They have to be
 placed in the "Doors:Filebase/Headers/" directory with the filename:

 ??.ans

 ?? = Section Number.

 eXAMPLE: I want to display an ansi above file area 23 then I'd call the
          ansi file "Doors:Filebase/Headers/23.ans".

 There are 3 other header files you can use:

 Doors:Filebase/Headers/.ans          Global list
 Doors:Filebase/Headers/NewFile.ans   NewFiles check
 Doors:Filebase/Headers/Lnk??.ans     Linked areas no. ?? (eg: Lnk1.ans)

@endnode
@node "10" "File Lister Express (FLE) by Peter Zelezny & Glen Martin"

 .-------------------.     _   /|
 |                   |     \'o.O'
 |  Linked Sections  |     =(_._)=
 |                   |        U    FLE (c) Glen Martin of GREMLiNS BBS
 `-------------------'

 This feature is simular to MAX's Lnk1, Lnk2, etc feature. You may want to
 have options like the following:

 (G)imme All iBM Files
 (L)ink All Amiga Files

 To do this you'd configure MAXs BBS like this:

 KEY    FUNC   EXTRA   LOWAXS  HiGHAXS  FiLE/PATH/DOOR
  G      34      0        0     10000    FLE:ListFiles LNK1
  L      34      0        0     10000    FLE:ListFiles LNK2

 nOTE: You can only have 2 LNK's, but more may work (a little buggy?).

 The format for the LNK files are shown below:

 Link name
 -
 Section number
 Section number
 Section number
 .....

 eXAMPLE:

 Amiga Files Linked
 -
 20
 21
 22
 23

 With the above example, the lister would list sections 20 to 23 when asked
 to list LNK1. There is a short cut way of doing it.

 eXAMPLE:

 Amiga Files Linked
 -
 20-25
 28-37

 The above example would list areas 20 to 25 and 28 to 37.

@endnode
@node "11" "File Lister Express (FLE) by Peter Zelezny & Glen Martin"

 .----------.     _   /|
 |          |     \'o.O'
 |  FileEd  |     =(_._)=
 |          |        U    FLE (c) Glen Martin of GREMLiNS BBS
 `----------'

      tYPE: MAXs BBS door
 aRGUMENTS: FileEd [<public screen name>]

 FileEd allows you to scroll thru' the filebase and view the file
 descriptions, etc. You can delete files, check filebase, etc. There
 are many more features via the pull-down menus, which you will learn.

 .----------------------------.
 | Public Screen Name feature |
 `----------------------------'

 This can be used to make FileEd open it's window on a screen other than
 workbench.

 eXAMPLES:

 FileED TERM
 FileED DiRWORK_1

 You just have to find out the exact screen name of the screen you want
 to use and type it in as FileEd's first and only argument. 

 nOTE: Public screen names are case sensative.
 
 .------------------.
 | Edit Desc button |
 `------------------'

 When you select to edit a file description, the editor CED is run so
 you can edit them and then save/quit CED. Press any key on FileEd and
 the new description will appear.

 nOTE: You can go through the file list using the up and down cursor keys.

 aTTENTiON: Do not add files using FileED, it is a little buggy. The best
            way to add files is to log onto the BBS, as follows:

            Log onto the BBS, goto the file area you wish to upload the
            files too, and execute upload. When the upload sequence has
            started, move(copy) the files you wish to "add" into the
            directory "TMP<node number>" in your files directory. When
            you have done so, then quit the upload sequence. You will
            then have to enter the file descriptions or a file_id.diz
            will be unpacked if one found.

@endnode
@node "12" "File Lister Express (FLE) by Peter Zelezny & Glen Martin"

 .--------------.     _   /|
 |              |     \'o.O'
 |  FLE_Config  |     =(_._)=
 |              |        U    FLE (c) Glen Martin of GREMLiNS BBS
 `--------------'

      tYPE: Shell program
 aRGUMENTS: FLE_Config

 Allows you to set a few FLE options, etc.

 .--------------------.
 | Check NewFiles AXS |
 `--------------------'

 Minimum access required to check for new files.

 .------------.
 | Assume AXS |
 `------------'

 If this box is ticked, a user's ratios/limits will change if their
 access level in MAX's normal user editor changes. It will change in
 accordance to the UserDefaults.txt config. This happens when a user
 passes thru' the NewFiles door.

 .------------.
 | Upload Log |
 `------------'

 Create an upload log or not?

 .--------------.
 | CLS in FList |
 `--------------'

 Each full screen of a file listing clears screen or scrolls up?

@endnode
@node "13" "File Lister Express (FLE) by Peter Zelezny & Glen Martin"

 .----------.     _   /|
 |          |     \'o.O'
 |  UserEd  |     =(_._)=
 |          |        U    FLE (c) Glen Martin of GREMLiNS BBS
 `----------'

      tYPE: Shell program
 aRGUMENTS: UserEd

 UserED is for editing ratios/limits and signatures, etc of users.

 .------------.
 | Membership |
 `------------'

 If the "date of membership expiery" is set to a valid date, FLE will
 down-grade the current user to the "time limit after expiery" and
 "access level after expiery" once that date has been reached.

 .--------------------.
 | Conditional Change |
 `--------------------'

 Changes current user settings to a another axs.


 nOTE: You can go through the user list using the up and down cursor
       keys, but don't do this too much as it's a little buggy.

 aTTENTiON: Do not use FileED to delete users, as it is unstable. Use
            the shell utility called "FLE_deluser" to delete users.
            Upon running it, it will prompt for a users name to delete.
            If there is a userfile (eg: FLE:users/G.user) sized 0k, you
            must delete this file as it will screw up the UserEd when run.

@endnode
@node "14" "File Lister Express (FLE) by Peter Zelezny & Glen Martin"

 .-------------.     _   /|
 |             |     \'o.O'
 |  New Files  |     =(_._)=
 |             |        U    FLE (c) Glen Martin of GREMLiNS BBS
 `-------------'

      tYPE: MAXs BBS door
 aRGUMENTS: NewFiles [<layout number>]

 You have to run the "Newfiles" door somewhere in the login sequence,
 this could be in maindoor.text or simular.

 Also, for users to edit their check for New Files flag at log in, you
 must configure MAXs BBS menu editor like the following:

 KEY    FUNC   EXTRA   LOWAXS  HiGHAXS  FiLE/PATH/DOOR
  N      34      0        0     10000    FLE:NewFiles CONFiG

@endnode
@node "15" "File Lister Express (FLE) by Peter Zelezny & Glen Martin"

 .-----------------.     _   /|
 |                 |     \'o.O'
 |  FLE Text List  |     =(_._)=
 |                 |        U    FLE (c) Glen Martin of GREMLiNS BBS
 `-----------------'

      tYPE: MAXs BBS door
 aRGUMENTS: FLETextList <list name>
 
 FLETextList allows your users to download the filelist. It is sent
 to them as a ascii text file or Amiga guide file (their choice). 

 Of course, only file areas to which they have access will be included
 in the list.

 The door also allows the users to compress the list before downloading, and
 the pack commands and archive types are stored in Config/PackFileCMDS.txt.

 eXAMPLE aRGUMENT:  FLE:FLETextList Ram:BBS_files

 Do not put an extension on the filename because a .TXT or .GUiDE extension
 will be added automatically. Also, choose a directory in which there'll
 be enough room. A filebase with 1,000 files will take about 100,000 bytes.

@endnode
@node "16" "File Lister Express (FLE) by Peter Zelezny & Glen Martin"

 .-----------------.     _   /|
 |                 |     \'o.O'
 |  FLE Tic Adder  |     =(_._)=
 |                 |        U    FLE (c) Glen Martin of GREMLiNS BBS
 `-----------------'

      tYPE: Shell program
 aRGUMENTS: FLE_TicAdder <section number>
 
 If you do not recieve netmail or echo mail then this program is useless
 to you. It adds any incoming files (files from your nets) to the normal
 file list. It does this by processing the *.tic file which gives the
 program the file's description. The section number is the section you
 want all inbound tic files to go into.

 nOTE: This program would normally be run in a script after mail import.

@endnode
@node "17" "File Lister Express (FLE) by Peter Zelezny & Glen Martin"

 .---------------.     _   /|
 |               |     \'o.O'
 |  ShowFLEAnsi  |     =(_._)=
 |               |        U    FLE (c) Glen Martin of GREMLiNS BBS
 `---------------'

      tYPE: MAXs BBS door
 aRGUMENTS: ShowFLEAnsi <filepath/ansi_filename>

 This door is used to display ansi's onto the remote and local screen.
 The difference is that it gives you FLE auto inserts to play with. MAXs
 normal auto inserts will also work as normal.

 .------------------.
 | FLE Auto Inserts |
 `------------------'

 &FR     File Ratio
 &KR     Kilo Byte Ratio

 &FC     File Credits remaining
 &KC     Kilo Byte Credits remaining

 &KU     Kilo Bytes user has uploaded
 &KD     Kilo Bytes user has downloaded

 &DL     User's daily download limit

 &US     User's upload signature
 &PR     Protocol name (not just the number!)
 &PB     This user's personal best CPS rate
 &MA     Does the user have marked files, returns "Yes" or "No"

 &NF     Number of active files

@endnode
@node "18" "File Lister Express (FLE) by Peter Zelezny & Glen Martin"

 .---------------.     _   /|
 |               |     \'o.O'
 |  Maintenance  |     =(_._)=
 |               |        U    FLE (c) Glen Martin of GREMLiNS BBS
 `---------------'

 .--------------.
 | FLE Programs |
 `--------------'

 There are six programs which you can run from WB or Shell:

 FileED           -   Delete files, make files public, etc.
 UserED           -   Change user's ratio's and daily limits, etc.
 FLE_Optimiser    -   Maintenance (optimising).
 FLE_Config       -   GUi configuration program.
 FLE_TicAdder     -   Add inbound tic files to filebase.
 FLE_Killdir      -   Cleans up your HD, deletes unwanted dirs.
 FLE_Renumber     -   Change an existing section number to an unused
                      section number.

 .-----------------.
 | FileEd Checkers |
 `-----------------'

 These 3 checkers are run via FileEd:

 FileChecker      -   Check to see if files in the list actually exist
                      on your harddisk. It also fixes filesizes. There
                      is also an "auto-delete" File Checker. When file
                      checker is run, it prompts you with any probs,
                      the "auto-delete" File Checker (FLEextras) will
                      not prompt you and fix things as it runs. Just
                      rename it as FileChecker if this version used.

 LostFilesCheck   -   Checks for files that are on your harddisk's
                      filepaths but have not been added into the list.

 FileDupCheck     -   Checks for duplicate files. First it checks to
                      see if there are any files in your filebase with
                      the same filesize, if yes then it compares the
                      files and if it finds they are the same (might
                      just have a different name) then you are given
                      the option to delete one.

 .-------------------.
 | The FLE_Optimiser |
 `-------------------'

 I suggest you run this once a week or so, its quite a lengthy process
 so don't do it too often (3 minutes per 1,000 files on slow systems).

 nOTE: You must run FLE_Optimiser when you add new or delete sections.

@endnode
@node "19" "File Lister Express (FLE) by Peter Zelezny & Glen Martin"

 .-----------------.     _   /|
 |                 |     \'o.O'
 |  Multiline BBS  |     =(_._)=
 |                 |        U    FLE (c) Glen Martin of GREMLiNS BBS
 `-----------------'

 FLE is completely multiline BBS compatable. All you have to do is create
 some extra directories. You may have noticed that FLE created a
 Files:TMP1/ directory, so all you have to do is create more like that
 for your other nodes.

 eXAMPLE: You are running a 2 line bbs, then just create Files:TMP2/, the
          directory for node 1 would have already been made.

 nOTE: TMP0 directory is for local mode. If you are running MAXsPro, you
       can delete TMP0 as it's not used.

 aTTENTiON: You MUST be using version 0.83 or higher for proper Multiline
            Support!

@endnode
@node "20" "File Lister Express (FLE) by Peter Zelezny & Glen Martin"

 .-------------.     _   /|
 |             |     \'o.O'
 |  Debugging  |     =(_._)=
 |             |        U    FLE (c) Glen Martin of GREMLiNS BBS
 `-------------'

 .------------------------------+---------------------------------------.
 | Problem                      | Solution/Comment                      |
 +------------------------------+---------------------------------------+
 | Get an "unknown error" if I  |                                       |
 | try to download or upload    | Run NewFiles in the login sequence.   |
 +------------------------------+---------------------------------------+
 | When a user selects download |                                       |
 | his/her marked files appear  |                                       |
 | and then disappear and       | This user is low on KB credits.       |
 | doesn't send any of them     |                                       |
 +------------------------------+---------------------------------------+
 | Users need to hit return,    |                                       |
 | when downloading, between    | Make line 182 blank in MAXs text cfg. |
 | each file                    |                                       |
 +------------------------------+---------------------------------------+
 | File is not online, or can't | Make sure you have Filepaths.text     |
 | be found                     | present in your Files directory, with |
 |                              | with all correct file paths.          |
 +------------------------------+---------------------------------------+
 | Corrupt filebase, ie: files  | Delete all data files in datafiles/   |
 | in wrong areas when listed   | dir except the "filelist.data" and    |
 |                              | then run FLE_Optimiser.               |
 +------------------------------+---------------------------------------+
 | Other errors, reqestors, etc | A prob with config, your system type? |
 |                              | FLE's not that perfect ... :-)        |
 `------------------------------+---------------------------------------'

@endnode
